She showed up in early October and she will probably stay until March. Six months of Pelop 🥺🥺🥺
Pelop face reveal (her species can change colours and textures depending on her environment, she can be grey and sometimes brown, and at night her emerald spots become vivid) https://t.co/GDgcoLrXU8

And there she was, sitting calmly in the sink like she never left. 

Now I'm sitting on the couch watching her walk across the carpet, fiddle with my blinds and make herself at home because she lives here. I am so, so happy.
But then an hour ago I heard a plop sound.

I must have checked twenty times. Over and over. And realising how much this little frog meant to me, how much I cared about her. The sun set and there was no plopping noises from the laundry as she moved about. It was so quiet. My eyes still hurt.

I even shone a torch into it and there was nothing. I found myself coming back hourly to look - and even stepping into the laundry made my house feel void of life.

I spent most of today crying. And feeling stupid for crying over a frog, not sure if anyone would understand why.

It's not unusual for Pelop to leave for a few days, sometimes even a week or two, during breeding season (to lay baby Pelopette tadpoles) but when I couldn't find her last night I had the worst feeling.

When I got up this morning I couldn't see her nose poking out of the drain.
That's her name btw. Pelop. I named her after an alien OC in one of Ree's fics. Maybe I would have given her a sweeter name if I knew she would come back year after year.

I have two very large dogs and I often have to coax the frog to climb up the wall so she's safe and out of reach. She always does it begrudgingly (she's too reckless).

But last night I saw my dog eating something large at the back door, and I couldn't find Pelop anywhere.

Every morning I get up and look for her nose poking out of the drain that she lives in.

Every night I watch her slip under the crack of the laundry door so she can eat bugs in my backyard. Sometimes she just hops into my room and rests instead, I don't know why.

Although there's always lots of frogs at my house, I've never seen another of her species. It's only her - and I'm always surprised when she comes back. But over the pandemic and especially while WFH she's been an important, exciting, fond piece of my daily life.

She stays for a few months and then she goes. She always sits in the same places - the sink, my bedroom windowsill, the railing of my bar stool. She is so beautiful and calm - I've never bothered or touched her (except to scoop her into jars and relocate her when in danger).

Through the day she sleeps in the drain and I can always see her nose poking out. At night she walks through my house like she owns it. She climbs up the walls, goes into my bedroom, walks in front of the TV. One time she jumped on my leg to get a ride across the house.

There's a Peron's Tree Frog that's showed up at my house for the past couple of summers. She crawls up through the drain and sits on my laundry sink.

At first I would relocate her but no matter how many times I'd put her outside, she'd come back in.
